# Post-push GitHub Actions (mandatory)

This is a **rule**, not an optional skill. Apply on every agent session in this repo.

## When this applies

- You ran **`git push`** on the current branch, **or**
- You are about to mark work **done** / open or update a PR / tell the user "finished" — and your commits are already pushed or will be pushed now.

If this push did **not** trigger any workflow (check path filters in `.github/workflows/*.yml`), skip monitoring.

## What to watch

Only workflow runs **triggered by the latest push** on **the current branch** (e.g. `CI`, and `Build release EXE` when path filters match). Do not chase unrelated runs on `main`, other branches, or old SHAs.

Wait until every triggered run has a final conclusion (`success`, `failure`, or `cancelled`).

```bash
gh run list --branch "$(git rev-parse --abbrev-ref HEAD)" --limit 10
gh run watch --exit-status   # or watch each in-progress run id
```

**Windows `build-windows` / App.Tests must pass** — Ubuntu-only green is not enough.

## If something is red

1. `gh run view <run-id> --log-failed` — find the first real error.
2. If the failure is **fixable in this repo** (tests, build scripts, workflow YAML, app code): fix → commit → **push** → go back to **What to watch** for the **new** push.
3. That is the intentional loop: **push → wait for triggered Actions → fix → push → wait again** until all triggered runs are green.

## When to stop the loop (not infinite)

| Stop | Reason |
|------|--------|
| **All triggered runs `success`** | Done — report run IDs and green status. |
| **Failure not fixable in code** | Secrets, billing, GitHub outage, missing org permission — report; do not spam empty commits. |
| **Same failure after 2 fix-and-push rounds** | Escalate to the user with logs and hypothesis. |
| **Cannot run required environment** | e.g. Windows-only failure and agent has no Windows — report limitation; do not claim CI is green. |

